[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The four reviewers do not have conflicting findings. The Security and Architecture experts overlap on the customer-managed KMS keys per data class (Finding S1 / A2) which is the same finding viewed through two lenses. The late-record-and-watermark problem (Finding A1) is a streaming-correctness concern that the Architecture expert surfaced; the Security expert did not flag it because it is not a security-or-compliance issue (the data is correctly encrypted and audited; it is just systematically biased). The CloudTrail data events finding (S2) intersects with the customer-managed-KMS-keys finding (S1) since the audit-trail integrity contract depends on per-data-class KMS keys for proper attribution. The Networking expert's VPC-endpoint enumeration (Finding N1) is the same chapter-pattern finding from 12.2 and reinforces the chapter-editor's job of consolidating these primitives.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Priority ordering:** A1 (late-record and watermark) before S1 / A2 (customer-managed KMS keys per data class) because the streaming-correctness contract is the foundational discipline for an hourly forecasting pipeline; without it, the model's training data and inference-time features are systematically biased and no amount of encryption hygiene fixes that. The customer-managed-KMS-keys finding is the regulatory baseline that must be correct on day one and is similarly elevated to HIGH. The remaining MEDIUM findings cluster around production-readiness gaps that the recipe correctly elevates in "Why This Isn't Production-Ready" but does not architecturally specify.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Chapter-pattern consolidation note:** Recipe 12.3 is the third recipe in Chapter 12 and the second to be expert-reviewed (12.2's expert review is in `reviews/chapter12.02-expert-review.md`; 12.1's expert review has not yet been written). The customer-managed-KMS-keys-per-data-class pattern, the Step-Functions-retry-and-DLQ pattern, and the VPC-endpoint enumeration pattern are repeated findings between 12.2 and 12.3; the chapter editor should plan to consolidate these into a chapter-level architectural baseline rather than restating them in each recipe. The late-record-and-watermark pattern is specific to streaming recipes (12.3 is the first in the chapter; 12.4 lab result trends and 12.7 vital sign trajectories will likely have similar surfaces) and the time-zone-and-DST handling pattern is specific to hourly-or-finer-granularity recipes (also 12.3, 12.7, plus parts of 12.5).
